b Khan]]''<ref>[http://ittefaq.com.bd/content/2010/12/15/news0508.htm Shakib Khan receiving award from journalist]. Ittefaq.com.bd. Retrieved 2 September 2011.</ref>\n\n; Babisas Award\n* Winner: Best actor for ''[[Number One Shakib Khan]]'' 2010<ref name=\"pa18Sep2010\">{{cite news |script-title=bn:\u098f\u09ac\u09be\u09b0 \u0988\u09a6\u09c7\u0993 \u09b6\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09ac\u09c7\u09b0 \u099b\u09ac\u09bf\u09b0 \u09b8\u09be\u09ab\u09b2\u09cd\u09af |url=http://www.prothom-alo.com/detail/date/2010-09-18/news/94145 |language=bn |newspaper=Prothom Alo |date=18 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106073425/http://www.prothom-alo.com/detail/date/2010-09-18/news/94145 |archive-date=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n; Showbiz Award 2010\n* Winner: Best actor for ''Bhalobashar Lal Golap''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120330150945/http://statusbd.com/actor-shakib-khan-the-king-of-bangla-cinema-dhallywood.html Actor Shakib Khan | The King of Bangla Cinema (Dhallywood)]. Statusbd.com. Retrieved 2 September 2011.</ref>\n; 4th Cholochitra Mela 2012\n* Special award&nbsp;\u2013 honoured as new generation actors\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Film soundtracks===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"width:80%;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Song\n|-\n| 2011\n| ''[[Moner Jala]]''\n| \"Ami Chokh Tule Takalei Surjo Lukay\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Shakib's song coming under Anupam\u2019s banner |url=http://news.priyo.com/entertainment/2011/jan/29/18453/shakib%E2%80%99s-song-coming-under-anupam%E2%80%99s-banner |newspaper=Priyo News |access-date=2 September 2011}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''[[Purno Doirgho Prem Kahini]]''\n| \"O Priyo Ami Tomar Hote Chai\"<ref name=\"pa23Jan2014\">{{cite news |script-title=bn:'\u09aa\u09c2\u09b0\u09cd\u09a3\u09a6\u09c8\u09b0\u09cd\u0998\u09cd\u09af \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09ae \u0995\u09be\u09b9\u09bf\u09a8\u09bf'\u09b0 \u09b8\u09c7\u099e\u09cd\u099a\u09c1\u09b0\u09bf |trans-title='Purno Doirgho Prem Kahini' Century |url=http://www.prothom-alo.com/entertainment/article/130183/ |language=bn |work=Prothom Alo |date=23 January 2014 |accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Television appearances==\n* Eid special episodes&nbsp;\u2013 ''Amar Ami'' (2009)... Guest\n* Eid special Talk Show&nbsp;\u2013 ''Nokhotro Jugol'' (2010).... Guest\n* Etv special show&nbsp;\u2013 ''Hot Sit With King Khan Shakib'' (2011)\n* Eid special&nbsp;\u2013 ''Ke Hotey Chay Kotipoti'' (2011)...Guest\n* Eid special- ''Prio Juti'' (2011)...Guest\n* Eid special- ''Tin Tarar Golpo'' (2011)...Guest\n* Eid special- ''Amader Devdas'' (2012)...Guest<ref>[http://www.dainikdestiny.com/index.php?view=details&type=main&cat_id=1&menu_id=6&pub_no=364&news_type_id=1&index=2&archiev=yes&arch_date=11-08-2012 Amader Devdas].dainikdestiny.com. Retrieved 12 September 2012.</ref>\n* Eid special- ''SuperStar(2012)''...Guest<ref>[https://archive.is/20130127054612/http://jantechaydesh.com/?p=5715 ''SuperStar'' Shakib w/ Mim & Apu]. jantechaydesh.com. Retrieved 12 September 2012.</ref>\n* Eid special- ''Star Night with Shakib Khan''(2012)...Guest<ref>{{cite news |script-title=bn:\u09b6\u09be\u0995\u09bf\u09ac \u0996\u09be\u09a8\u09c7\u09b0 \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09a5\u09ae \u09aa\u09cd\u09b0\u09c7\u09ae |trans-title=Shakib Khan's first love |url=http://bangla.bdnews.com/news/18901 |language=bn |newspaper=bdnews.com |access-date=12 September 2012}}</ref>\n* Eid special&nbsp;\u2013 ''Shudhui Adda''...Guest\n\n===Special appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Years\n! Film\n! Role\n|-\n|2014\n|''Ke Apon Ke Por''\n| Himself\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Dobir Saheber Songsar]]''\n| Cameo\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''Ek Cup Cha''\n| Cameo\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dhallywood]]\n* [[Cinema of Bangladesh]]\n* [[List of Bangladeshi actors]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|3492497|Shakib Khan}}\n* {{facebook|Iamshakibkhanbd}}\n\n{{Bangladesh National Film Award Best Actor}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Khan, Shakib}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Bengali male actors]]\n[[Category:People from Dhaka]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male singers]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi male film actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Bengali cinema]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the National Film Awards (Bangladesh)]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bangladeshi male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century Bangladeshi singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi film producers]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shakib_Khan"}
{"title_page": "Iola Leal Riesco", "text_new": "'''Iola Leal Riesco''' (born 4 July 1977 in [[Lugo]], [[Spain]]) is an environmental and social activist working for [[European Forest Institute]]<ref>[http://www.efi.int EFI site]</ref> and [[Well Grounded]].<ref>[http://www.well-grounded.org/ Well Grounded site]</ref> Her educational background is in the field of forest and human ecology. Since 2003 she has been working to help solve the challenges of integrating environmental issues into EC Aid policies and improve governance in forests globally. She is currently working on EU policies and following closely the EU action plan for [http://ec.europa.eu/development/policies/9interventionareas/environment/forest/forestry_intro_en.cfm Forest Law Enforcement, Governance and Trade].<ref>The Courier [http://www.acp-eucourier.info/Forests-under-close-surve.113.0.html Issue Nr II - September/October 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908044511/http://www.acp-eucourier.info/Forests-under-close-surve.113.0.html |date=2008-09-08 }}</ref> In 2010, she set up with [[Cath Long]] the organisation Well Grounded, which provides services and support to African civil society organisations working with communities to help them assert their rights and to improve forest governance.\n\nPrior to joining EFI, she worked for [[FERN]],<ref>[http://www.fern.org/node/4498 FERN site]</ref> [[Amazonia Assemblea de Solidaritat]], [[Skamot Verd]] and [[Asociaci\u00f3n pola defensa da r\u00eda]]. She is a Master of Science in Biology by the [[University of Barcelona]].\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''[http://www.wu-wien.ac.at/inst/fsnu/vienna/papers/olearius.pdf From an European Court of Auditors\u2019 Report to a learning process? The challenge to integrate the environment into the European Community\u2019s development assistance]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'' Olearius A, Leal Riesco I & Nicholson S (2008)\n* ''[http://www.fern.org/media/documents/document_4024_4036.pdf Transparency and availability of EC aid documentation, a review]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}''. Nicholson S & Leal Riesco I (2007) FERN-WWF-BirdLife Report, September 2007.\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090106045941/http://www.fern.org/media/documents/document_3914_3917.pdf Provoking change - A toolkit for African NGOs]''. [[Saskia Ozinga]] and Iola Leal Riesco (2007)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20071107080209/http://www.fern.org/media/documents/document_3665_3666.pdf Integrating environmental issues in the next round of co-operation agreements between the EU and ACP countries]'' Leal Riesco I. FERN's EC Forest Platform Briefing Note Issue 04, June 2006\n* {{cite journal|last1=Rautio|first1=Pasi|last2=Markkola|first2=Annamari|last3=Martel|first3=Jocelyn|last4=Tuomi|first4=Juha|last5=Harma|first5=Esa|last6=Kuikka|first6=Karita|last7=Siitonen|first7=Annika|last8=Riesco|first8=Iola Leal|last9=Roitto|first9=Marja|title=Developmental plasticity in birch leaves: defoliation causes a shift from glandular to nonglandular trichomes|journal=Oikos|volume=98|issue=3|year=2002|pages=437\u2013446|issn=0030-1299|doi=10.1034/j.1600-0706.2002.980308.x}}\n* ''Women and Environment still run behind''. Leal Riesco I. (2003) Phoenix magazine, July: European Constitution Pg. 40.\n* ''Economic Impact of transgenics in the Agro-food industry''. Leal Riesco I (2003) EU Council, internal report.\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20070712202758/http://www.fern.org/media/documents/document_837_838.pdf Forest loss and human health: focus on EU policies and practices]'' Leal Riesco I (2005) FERN Briefing Note, Brussels.\n* ''Muller, Natureza e Tecnolox\u00eda'' Leal Riesco I (2001). XVIII Galician Philosophy Week: Philosophy and Technology, Pontevedra. Aula Castelao de Filosof\u00eda & Vigo University.\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20080509195822/http://www.pangea.org/~vmitjans/eng_gen/eng_gen.htm Enginyeria gen\u00e8tica... \u00bfsense fronteres?]'' Sergi Rodr\u00edguez Toh\u00e0, Eul\u00e0lia Gass\u00f3 i Miracle i Iola Leal Riesco. Ecoilla n\u00ba12, Pg.1-4, December 1997 & Bolet\u00edn n\u00ba 9 de la Xarxa de Consum Solidari de Barcelona, December 1998]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.efi.int EFI]\n* [http://www.well-grounded.org Well Grounded]\n* [http://www.fern.org FERN]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riesco, Iola Leal}}\n[[Category:Spanish environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Spanish women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:People from Lugo]]\n[[Category:Forest governance]]\n[[Category:Forestry in Spain]]\n", "text_old": "'''Iola Leal Riesco''' (born 4 July 1977 in [[Lugo]], [[Spain]]) is an environmental and social activist working for [[European Forest Institute]]<ref>[http://www.efi.int EFI site]</ref> and [[Well Grounded]].<ref>[http://www.well-grounded.org/ Well Grounded site]</ref> Her educational background is in the field of forest and human ecology. Since 2003 she has been working to help solve the challenges of integrating environmental issues into EC Aid policies and improve governance in forests globally. She is currently working on EU policies and following closely the EU action plan for [http://ec.europa.eu/development/policies/9interventionareas/environment/forest/forestry_intro_en.cfm Forest Law Enforcement, Governance and Trade].<ref>The Courier [http://www.acp-eucourier.info/Forests-under-close-surve.113.0.html Issue Nr II - September/October 2007] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080908044511/http://www.acp-eucourier.info/Forests-under-close-surve.113.0.html |date=2008-09-08 }}</ref> In 2010, she set up with [[Cath Long]] the organisation Well Grounded, which provides services and support to African civil society organisations working with communities to help them assert their rights and to improve forest governance.\n\nPrior to joining EFI, she worked for [[FERN]],<ref>[http://www.fern.org/node/4498 FERN site]</ref> [[Amazonia Assemblea de Solidaritat]], [[Skamot Verd]] and [[Asociaci\u00f3n pola defensa da r\u00eda]]. She is a Master of Science in Biology by the [[University of Barcelona]].\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''[http://www.wu-wien.ac.at/inst/fsnu/vienna/papers/olearius.pdf From an European Court of Auditors\u2019 Report to a learning process? The challenge to integrate the environment into the European Community\u2019s development assistance]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}'' Olearius A, Leal Riesco I & Nicholson S (2008)\n* ''[http://www.fern.org/media/documents/document_4024_4036.pdf Transparency and availability of EC aid documentation, a review]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}''. Nicholson S & Leal Riesco I (2007) FERN-WWF-BirdLife Report, September 2007.\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090106045941/http://www.fern.org/media/documents/document_3914_3917.pdf Provoking change - A toolkit for African NGOs]''. [[Saskia Ozinga]] and Iola Leal Riesco (2007)\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20071107080209/http://www.fern.org/media/documents/document_3665_3666.pdf Integrating environmental issues in the next round of co-operation agreements between the EU and ACP countries]'' Leal Riesco I. FERN\u2019s EC Forest Platform Briefing Note Issue 04, June 2006\n* {{cite journal|last1=Rautio|first1=Pasi|last2=Markkola|first2=Annamari|last3=Martel|first3=Jocelyn|last4=Tuomi|first4=Juha|last5=Harma|first5=Esa|last6=Kuikka|first6=Karita|last7=Siitonen|first7=Annika|last8=Riesco|first8=Iola Leal|last9=Roitto|first9=Marja|title=Developmental plasticity in birch leaves: defoliation causes a shift from glandular to nonglandular trichomes|journal=Oikos|volume=98|issue=3|year=2002|pages=437\u2013446|issn=0030-1299|doi=10.1034/j.1600-0706.2002.980308.x}}\n* ''Women and Environment still run behind''. Leal Riesco I. (2003) Phoenix magazine, July: European Constitution Pg. 40.\n* ''Economic Impact of transgenics in the Agro-food industry''. Leal Riesco I (2003) EU Council, internal report.\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20070712202758/http://www.fern.org/media/documents/document_837_838.pdf Forest loss and human health: focus on EU policies and practices]'' Leal Riesco I (2005) FERN Briefing Note, Brussels.\n* ''Muller, Natureza e Tecnolox\u00eda'' Leal Riesco I (2001). XVIII Galician Philosophy Week: Philosophy and Technology, Pontevedra. Aula Castelao de Filosof\u00eda & Vigo University.\n* ''[https://web.archive.org/web/20080509195822/http://www.pangea.org/~vmitjans/eng_gen/eng_gen.htm Enginyeria gen\u00e8tica... \u00bfsense fronteres?]'' Sergi Rodr\u00edguez Toh\u00e0, Eul\u00e0lia Gass\u00f3 i Miracle i Iola Leal Riesco. Ecoilla n\u00ba12, Pg.1-4, December 1997 & Bolet\u00edn n\u00ba 9 de la Xarxa de Consum Solidari de Barcelona, December 1998]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.efi.int EFI]\n* [http://www.well-grounded.org Well Grounded]\n* [http://www.fern.org FERN]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Riesco, Iola Leal}}\n[[Category:Spanish environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Spanish women environmentalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:People from Lugo]]\n[[Category:Forest governance]]\n[[Category:Forestry in Spain]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iola_Leal_Riesco"}
{"title_page": "Byelorussian Central Council", "text_new": "{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Byelorussian Central Council\n| native_name = ''Wei\u00dfruthenischer Zentralrat''<br /> \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0426\u044d\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0430\n| jurisdiction = ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]'':<br />''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland#Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien (Belarus)|Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien]]''\n| seal = Seal of Belarusian Central Council.svg\n| seal_width = 140\n| logo = \n| type = Council\n| formed = 1 March 1943\n| dissolved = 2 July 1944\n| headquarters = [[Minsk]]\n| employees = \n| budget = \n| chief1_name = [[Hinrich Lohse]]\n| chief1_position = (''[[Reichskommissar]]'')\n| chief2_name = [[Wilhelm Kube]]\n| chief2_position = (''Generalreichskommissar'')\n| chief3_name = [[Radas\u0142a\u016d Astro\u016dski]]\n| chief3_position = (President)\n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency = '''Reich Minister for the'''<br />'''Occupied Eastern Territories''':<br />Rauchstra\u00dfe 17/18, [[Berlin]],<br />{{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n| website = \n}}\nThe '''Byelorussian Central Council''' or the '''Byelorussian  Central Rada''' ({{lang-be|\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0426\u044d\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0430, Bie\u0142aruskaja Centralnaja Rada}}; {{lang-de|Wei\u00dfruthenischer Zentralrat}}) was a [[Belarusians|Byelorussian]] representative body with limited governmental functions during World War II in  [[German occupation of Byelorussia during World War II|German-occupied Byelorussia]] (modern-day [[Belarus]]).<ref>(German) Dallin, Alexander (1958). ''Deutsche Herrschaft in Russland, 1941-1945: Eine Studie \u00fcber Besatzungspolitik'', pp. 234-236. Droste Verlag GmbH, D\u00fcsseldorf.</ref> It was established by [[Nazi Germany]] within ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]'' in 1943\u201344,<ref name=\"Wilson\"/> following a requests by [[Collaboration with the Axis Powers during World War II|collaborationist]] Belarusian politicians hoping to create an independent Belarusian state with support of Nazi Germany.<ref name=\"Wilson\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-2008-0042, Wei\u00dfrussland, Minsk, Geb\u00e4ude.jpg|thumb|left|The rade at Minsk, June 1943.]]\n[[File:Flag of Belarus (1918, 1991\u20131995).svg|thumb|left|Flag of the Byelorussian Central Council]]\nImmediately after the 1941 attack on the [[Territories of Poland annexed by the Soviet Union|Soviet positions]] in [[Operation Barbarossa]],<ref name=\"Browning349\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jHQdRHNdK44C&q=Bialystok#v=snippet&q=Bialystok&f=false | title=From War of Destruction to the Final Solution | publisher=U of Nebraska Press | work=The Origins of the Final Solution: The Evolution of Nazi Jewish Policy, September 1939-March 1942 | date=1 May 2007 | accessdate=6 December 2014 | author=Christopher R. Browning | pages=255\u2013349 | ISBN=0803203926 }}</ref> the mass persecution of Jews by the ''[[Schutzstaffel|SS]]'' forward units of ''[[Einsatzgruppe B]]'' began under the command of ''[[SS-Gruppenf\u00fchrer]]'' [[Arthur Nebe]].<ref name=\"nebe\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2rJqy2SkJqsC&pg=PA231&lpg=PA231&dq=Einsatzgruppe+Arthur+Nebe+Belarus&source=bl&ots=aYqrpRM8HC&sig=e_ajVZT7fT9CEhL93W5VWmtVsjU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xZDjVJerJMSzoQTg54HwBw&ved=0CFkQ6AEwEA#v=onepage&q=Einsatzgruppe%20Arthur%20Nebe%20Belarus&f=false | title=Nazi Policy on the Eastern Front, 1941: Total War, Genocide, and Radicalization | publisher=University Rochester Press | date=2012 | accessdate=17 February 2015 |author1=Alex J. Kay |author2=Jeff Rutherford |author3=David Stahel | page=231 | ISBN=1580464076}}</ref> Jews were massacred and ghettos were formed in dozens of towns with the participation of [[Collaboration with the Axis Powers during World War II|Byelorussian collaborators]] who were given various prominent roles.<ref name=\"jewishgen\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishgen.org/yizkor/belarus/bel160.html |title=From materials of the Extraordinary Commission (Ch.G.K. USSR) |publisher=JewishGen |work=Yizkor Book Project. Holocaust in Belorussia |date=20 Sep 2007 |accessdate=7 July 2014 |author=Lance Ackerfeld}}</ref> The [[Belarusian Auxiliary Police]] was established and deployed to murder operations particularly in February\u2013March 1942.<ref name=\"geni\">{{cite web |url=http://www.geni.com/projects/Shoah-in-Belarus/11081 |title=Shoah in Belarus |series=Death Squads, Massacres, Ghettos |publisher=Geni.com |year=2015 |accessdate= 17 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Operation Barbarossa|Germany's rapid conquest]], the ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland#Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien (Belarus)|Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien]]'' district of [[Reichskommissariat Ostland|RKO]] was formed which included the western and central parts of the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic]] in its 1941 borders (which included the towns of [[Hlybokaye]], [[Vileyka]], [[Navahrudak]] and other territories earlier annexed by the USSR from Poland). In 1942, the German civil authority was extended to Minsk, [[Slutsk]] and [[Barysaw]]. The area was to be made part of the Nazis' project of [[Lebensraum]] (\"living space\"), in which those deemed non-[[Aryan]] would be exterminated or expelled to make way for German colonists, while the remaining locals would be subject to forced [[Germanization]]. All attempts by the Byelorussian representatives to request self-governance for the occupied Byelorussia led to German repressions against those who voiced such requests.<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1976-127-31A, Wilhelm Kube in Minsk.jpg|thumb|right|''Generalreichskommissar'' [[Wilhelm Kube]] in [[Minsk]], May 1943]]\n''Generalreichskommissar'' [[Wilhelm Kube]] was appointed the German administrator of the area. He had his command center established in [[Minsk]] with a second ''Kommissar'' in [[Baranovichi]]. In September 1943, Kube was killed by his Byelorussian mistress, who planted a bomb in his bed coerced by the Soviet agents who knew where her son was.<ref name=\"Wilson-PDF\"/>\n\nIn order to drum up fresh troops for the front inside ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]'' and to stimulate support from the Belarusian population and elites,<ref name=hardzijenka/> General [[Reinhard Gehlen]] suggested to the German High Command that some concessions be made to the Belarusian collaborators in the form of a [[puppet state]].<ref name=\"Wilson-PDF\"/> The ''semi-autonomous'' local government was founded by Nazi Germany in December 1943, and named the Byelorussian  Central Council. [[Radas\u0142a\u016d Astro\u016dski]], the mayor of Smolensk at that time, was appointed its president.<ref name=\"Wilson\"/> General [[Curt von Gottberg|Kurt von Gottberg]] who replaced Kube, named the Belarusian politician [[Ivan Yermachenka]], arriving from Prague, the \"Advisor on Belarusian affairs\".<ref name=\"Wilson-PDF\">{{cite web |url=http://mizna.ru/docs/2/1212/conv_1/file1.pdf |title=The Traumatic Twentieth Century |publisher=Yale University Press |work=Belarus: the last European dictatorship |year=2011 |accessdate=10 July 2014 |author=Andrew Wilson |pages=109&ndash;110 |format=PDF file, direct download 16.4 MB |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714144611/http://mizna.ru/docs/2/1212/conv_1/file1.pdf |archivedate=14 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Functions and work==\nThe Byelorussian Central Council only had a limited role in governing, with the key decisions being taken by the German administration of the ''Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien''. The Council mostly managed social affairs as well as culture and education.<ref name=hardzijenka>{{cite web | url = http://www.bielarus.org/open.php?n=492&a=3 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060928014900/http://www.bielarus.org/open.php?n=492&a=3 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2006-09-28 | title = \u0414\u0410 \u040e\u0413\u041e\u0414\u041a\u0410\u040e \u0411\u0415\u041b\u0410\u0420\u0423\u0421\u041a\u0410\u0419 \u0426\u042d\u041d\u0422\u0420\u0410\u041b\u042c\u041d\u0410\u0419 \u0420\u0410\u0414\u042b - \u0420\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u0433\u0456 \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0433\u0430 \u0433\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u043a\u0430 | trans-title = The anniversary of the Belarusian Central Council - ideas from a young historian | last = Hardzijenka | first = Aleh | date = January 2004 | website = Bielarus.org | publisher = Bielarus Newspaper | access-date = 10 January 2017 | language = Belarusian }}</ref> The Council had twelve departments including: Education, science and culture; Propaganda and press; Social security; Finance; Youth affairs; Religion; Control; Administrative issues; Economy; National minorities; and [[Belarusian Home Defence|Home Defense]].<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\nThe Byelorussian Central Council oversaw the activities of Byelorussian civic organizations established earlier under German permission including: Union of Byelorussian Youth; Byelorussian Scientific Society; Byelorussian Cultural Association; Byelorussian Self-Help; and labour unions.<ref name=hardzijenka/> The Council has managed to widen the usage of the Byelorussian language in schools and in public life, worked on the opening of a university.<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\nUnlike earlier Byelorussian collaborationist organizations, the Byelorussian Central Council was better positioned with the German authorities to protect the interests of the Byelorussian population from the Germans.<ref name=hardzijenka/>{{better source|date=February 2017}}\n\n==Policy on religion==\nThe ''SS'' authorised an [[Autocephaly|autocephalous]] [[Belarusian Orthodox Church]] independent from the [[Patriarch of Moscow]] who, similarly, was used by the Soviet atheists to rally Russians against the Germans. The priests had considerable influence with the peasantry and actively supported the defeat of Soviet Russia, which had terrorized Christians in [[West Belarus]] after the joint Soviet [[Soviet invasion of Poland|invasion of Poland]] of September 17, 1939.<ref name=\"1000dokumente\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.1000dokumente.de/index.html?c=dokument_de&dokument=0025_pak&object=facsimile&pimage=1&v=100&nav=&l=de |type= facsimile |title= 100(0) Schl\u00fcsseldokumente |place= [[Germany|DE]] |accessdate= 17 September 2009 |ref= harv}}.</ref>\n\n==Byelorussian Home Defence (BKA)==\n{{Main|Byelorussian Home Defence}}\n  [[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1991-0206-506, Wei\u00dfrussland, Minsk.jpg|thumb|[[Byelorussian Home Defence]] (BKA) parading in [[Minsk]] <ref name=\"Wilson\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jZJntMQtkSYC&q=%28BKA%29 |title=Belarus: The Last European Dictatorship |publisher=Yale University Press |year=2011 |accessdate=10 July 2014 |author=Andrew Wilson |pages=109, 110, 113 |isbn=0300134355 | format=Google Books preview}}</ref>]]\nIn March 1944, the Byelorussian Central Council organized a universal military conscription among the young Belarusians. The Belarusian Home Defence Force (''Bielaruskaja Krajovaja Abarona'', BKA) was formed, with 28,000 soldiers ready for training, aided by a few thousand members of the [[Belarusian Auxiliary Police]] battalions.<ref name=\"Piotrowski155\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hC0-dk7vpM8C&q=%22forty+thousand+volunteers%22#v=snippet&q=%22forty%20thousand%20volunteers%22&f=false | title=Belorussian Collaboration | publisher=McFarland | work=Poland's Holocaust: Ethnic Strife, Collaboration with Occupying Forces and Genocide in the Second Republic, 1918-1947 | date=1998 | accessdate=6 February 2015 | author=Tadeusz Piotrowski | pages=155 | isbn=0786403713}}</ref>\n\nAfter the retreat of Germans from Byelorussia, the Byelorussian Home Defence was absorbed into ''[[30th Waffen Grenadier Division of the SS|30. Waffen-Grenadier-Division der SS-Russische No 2.]]''. This infantry division formed from the remnants of the [[29th Waffen-SS Division]], included both Belarusian and Ukrainian units. The Germans had set up an officers' school and issued uniforms with a [[Waffen-SS]] Storm-brigade Belarus designation. Orders were issued for Belarusian forces to be absorbed by [[Andrey Vlasov]]'s [[Russian Army of Liberation]]; but Astro\u016dski opposed this. He also sabotaged the idea of the \"[[Committee for the Liberation of the Peoples of Russia]]\", since he did not wanted to align himself with Russians.\n\nOther members of BKA and the Byelorussian Auxiliary Police were recruited by SS Colonel [[Otto Skorzeny]] for training in Dahlwitz near [[Berlin]], to make special undercover strikes behind the enemy lines. These units were part of a clandestine operation known as ''Liebes K\u00e4tzchen'' stretched from the Baltics to the Black Sea. The Byelorussian \"[[\u010corny Kot|Black Cat]]\" guerrilla group was led by [[Michas' Vitushka]]. They operated in [[Belavezha Forest]] (Bia\u0142owie\u017ca) against the Soviet forces in anti-communist operations throughout 1945 but with little success.<ref name=\"PartyzanFilm\">{{cite journal | url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/201323579/BielaruskiRezystans-1 | title=Belarusian Resistance, documentary by PartyzanFilm 2008 (transcript) | publisher=Scribd.com | work=Based on Bialoruski ruch oporu by Siarhiej Jorsz | date=January 22, 2014 | accessdate=19 February 2015 | author=Dawid Wowra}}</ref><ref name=\"wilson109\">Wilson 2011, [https://books.google.com/books?id=jZJntMQtkSYC&q=%22Black+Cat%22+#v=snippet&q=%22Black%20Cat%22&f=false  p. 109. Operation Black Cat.]</ref><ref name=\"MI6\">{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/mi6insidecovertw00dorr | url-access=registration | quote=Black Cat. | title=MI6: Inside the Covert World | publisher=Simon and Schuster | work=Belorussia | date=2002 | accessdate=19 February 2015 | author=Stephen Dorril | page=[https://archive.org/details/mi6insidecovertw00dorr/page/217 217] | ISBN=0743217780}}</ref><ref name=\"MJC167\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4zSGR3fBfUcC&q=%22Black+Cat%22#v=snippet&q=%22Black%20Cat%22&f=false | title=Intermarium: The Land between the Black and Baltic Seas | publisher=Transaction Publishers | work=The Second Soviet Occupation | date=2012 | accessdate=19 February 2015 | author=Marek Jan Chodakiewicz | page=167 }}</ref> Infiltrated by NKVD, they were destroyed in 1945.<ref name=\"Dudar\">{{cite web|url=http://geocities.com/dudar2000/Bcc.htm |title=Belarusian \"Black Cats\" of Otto Skorzeny |publisher=Internet Archive |work=John Loftus \"The Belarus Secret\", edited by Nathan Miller, Alfred A. Knopf Inc., New York, 1982. |ISBN=0-394-52292-3 |date=March 25, 1999 |accessdate=19 February 2015 |author=Dudar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025235435/http://geocities.com/dudar2000/Bcc.htm |archivedate=October 25, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Exile==\nIn 1944, with the advance of the [[Red Army]] towards the West, the Byelorussian Central Council evacuated with the retreating Germans to [[East Prussia]]n and [[Poland|Polish]] lands still under the control of Nazi Germany.\n\nA few days before the evacuation, the BCR held a congress in Minsk, titled the Second All-Byelorussian Congress. The meeting gathered 1039 delegates from various regions of Belarus and from Byelorussian emigre organizations.<ref name=hardz_2ubk>http://www.bielarus.org/open.php?n=497&a=10</ref> The congress confirmed the declaration of independence of Belarus and declared the Belarusian Central Council as the supreme Belarusian representative body. The aim of the meeting was for the BCR to gain legitimacy basing on a decision by representatives of the Belarusian society rather than on a decision by the German administration.<ref name=hardz_2ubk/> The organizers feared provocations from both Soviet partisans and the Germans.<ref name=hardz_2ubk/>\n\nAfter evacuation, the leadership of the BCR has formed the base for Byelorussian self-organization in the post-war camps for [[Displaced person]]s.<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\nAt the end of 1945, Astro\u016dski held a special meeting of the \"Byelorussian Central Committee\" which decided to dissolve the government in order to avoid accusation of collaboration with the Nazis.<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\nOn March 25, 1948, the Byelorussian Central Council renewed its activity in exile.<ref>[[Wojciech Roszkowski]], Jan Kofman (Hrsg.): ''Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century.'' Routledge, Abingdon u. a. 2015, {{ISBN|978-0-7656-1027-0}}, p. 39-40.</ref> It has been one of the main umbrella organizations of the Belarusian emigre community in the West till its de facto dissolution in 1995.\n\n==Presidents==\n* [[Radas\u0142a\u016d Astro\u016dski]] (1943 \u2014 1945 and 1948 \u2014 1976)\n* [[Nikandar Miadziejka]] (1977 \u2014 1987)\n* [[Michas Zuj]] (1988 \u2014 1995)\n* [[Vital Ciarpicki]] (1995)\n\n==See also==\n* [[German occupation of Byelorussia during World War II]]\n* [[Byelorussian collaboration with Nazi Germany]]\n* [[Byelorussia in World War II]]\n* [[Lokot Republic]] - native Russian state under indirect German control\n* [[Belarusian People's Republic]] - World War I-era Belarusian state\n* [[Byelorussian SSR]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Arnold Toynbee, Veronica Toynbee, ''et al.'', ''La Europa de Hitler'' (Spanish tr. of ''Hitler's Europe''), Ed Vergara, Barcelona, Esp, 1958 reprinted in 1986 by Madrid Sarpe D.L., Section VI: \"Occupied lands and Satellite Countries in East Europe\", Chapter II: Ostland, P.253-259. {{OCLC|434840263}}\n* Ostland Footnotes: P.253-259.\n\n{{WWIIHistory}}\n\n[[Category:Belarus in World War II]]\n[[Category:Belarusian collaboration with Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Belarusian Central Council]]\n[[Category:Belarusian independence movement]]\n[[Category:Reichskommissariat Ostland]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Soviet Union during World War II]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n[[Category:Collaboration with the Axis Powers]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox government agency\n| name = Belarusian Central Council\n| native_name = ''Wei\u00dfruthenischer Zentralrat''<br /> \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0426\u044d\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0430\n| jurisdiction = ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]'':<br />''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland#Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien (Belarus)|Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien]]''\n| seal = Seal of Belarusian Central Council.svg\n| seal_width = 140\n| logo = \n| type = Council\n| formed = 1 March 1943\n| dissolved = 2 July 1944\n| headquarters = [[Minsk]]\n| employees = \n| budget = \n| chief1_name = [[Hinrich Lohse]]\n| chief1_position = (''[[Reichskommissar]]'')\n| chief2_name = [[Wilhelm Kube]]\n| chief2_position = (''Generalreichskommissar'')\n| chief3_name = [[Radas\u0142a\u016d Astro\u016dski]]\n| chief3_position = (President)\n| chief4_name = \n| chief4_position = \n| chief5_name = \n| chief5_position = \n| chief6_name = \n| chief6_position = \n| chief7_name = \n| chief7_position = \n| chief8_name = \n| chief8_position = \n| chief9_name = \n| chief9_position = \n| parent_department = \n| parent_agency = '''Reich Minister for the'''<br />'''Occupied Eastern Territories''':<br />Rauchstra\u00dfe 17/18, [[Berlin]],<br />{{flag|Nazi Germany}}\n| website = \n}}\nThe '''Byelorussian Central Council''' or the '''Byelorussian  Central Rada''' ({{lang-be|\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0426\u044d\u043d\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0420\u0430\u0434\u0430, Bie\u0142aruskaja Centralnaja Rada}}; {{lang-de|Wei\u00dfruthenischer Zentralrat}}) was a [[Belarusians|Byelorussian]] representative body with limited governmental functions during World War II in  [[German occupation of Byelorussia during World War II|German-occupied Byelorussia]] (modern-day [[Belarus]]).<ref>(German) Dallin, Alexander (1958). ''Deutsche Herrschaft in Russland, 1941-1945: Eine Studie \u00fcber Besatzungspolitik'', pp. 234-236. Droste Verlag GmbH, D\u00fcsseldorf.</ref> It was established by [[Nazi Germany]] within ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]'' in 1943\u201344,<ref name=\"Wilson\"/> following a requests by [[Collaboration with the Axis Powers during World War II|collaborationist]] Belarusian politicians hoping to create an independent Belarusian state with support of Nazi Germany.<ref name=\"Wilson\"/>\n\n== Background ==\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-2008-0042, Wei\u00dfrussland, Minsk, Geb\u00e4ude.jpg|thumb|left|The rade at Minsk, June 1943.]]\n[[File:Flag of Belarus (1918, 1991\u20131995).svg|thumb|left|Flag of the Byelorussian Central Council]]\nImmediately after the 1941 attack on the [[Territories of Poland annexed by the Soviet Union|Soviet positions]] in [[Operation Barbarossa]],<ref name=\"Browning349\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jHQdRHNdK44C&q=Bialystok#v=snippet&q=Bialystok&f=false | title=From War of Destruction to the Final Solution | publisher=U of Nebraska Press | work=The Origins of the Final Solution: The Evolution of Nazi Jewish Policy, September 1939-March 1942 | date=1 May 2007 | accessdate=6 December 2014 | author=Christopher R. Browning | pages=255\u2013349 | ISBN=0803203926 }}</ref> the mass persecution of Jews by the ''[[Schutzstaffel|SS]]'' forward units of ''[[Einsatzgruppe B]]'' began under the command of ''[[SS-Gruppenf\u00fchrer]]'' [[Arthur Nebe]].<ref name=\"nebe\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2rJqy2SkJqsC&pg=PA231&lpg=PA231&dq=Einsatzgruppe+Arthur+Nebe+Belarus&source=bl&ots=aYqrpRM8HC&sig=e_ajVZT7fT9CEhL93W5VWmtVsjU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xZDjVJerJMSzoQTg54HwBw&ved=0CFkQ6AEwEA#v=onepage&q=Einsatzgruppe%20Arthur%20Nebe%20Belarus&f=false | title=Nazi Policy on the Eastern Front, 1941: Total War, Genocide, and Radicalization | publisher=University Rochester Press | date=2012 | accessdate=17 February 2015 |author1=Alex J. Kay |author2=Jeff Rutherford |author3=David Stahel | page=231 | ISBN=1580464076}}</ref> Jews were massacred and ghettos were formed in dozens of towns with the participation of [[Collaboration with the Axis Powers during World War II|Byelorussian collaborators]] who were given various prominent roles.<ref name=\"jewishgen\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishgen.org/yizkor/belarus/bel160.html |title=From materials of the Extraordinary Commission (Ch.G.K. USSR) |publisher=JewishGen |work=Yizkor Book Project. Holocaust in Belorussia |date=20 Sep 2007 |accessdate=7 July 2014 |author=Lance Ackerfeld}}</ref> The [[Belarusian Auxiliary Police]] was established and deployed to murder operations particularly in February\u2013March 1942.<ref name=\"geni\">{{cite web |url=http://www.geni.com/projects/Shoah-in-Belarus/11081 |title=Shoah in Belarus |series=Death Squads, Massacres, Ghettos |publisher=Geni.com |year=2015 |accessdate= 17 February 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Operation Barbarossa|Germany's rapid conquest]], the ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland#Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien (Belarus)|Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien]]'' district of [[Reichskommissariat Ostland|RKO]] was formed which included the western and central parts of the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic]] in its 1941 borders (which included the towns of [[Hlybokaye]], [[Vileyka]], [[Navahrudak]] and other territories earlier annexed by the USSR from Poland). In 1942, the German civil authority was extended to Minsk, [[Slutsk]] and [[Barysaw]]. The area was to be made part of the Nazis' project of [[Lebensraum]] (\"living space\"), in which those deemed non-[[Aryan]] would be exterminated or expelled to make way for German colonists, while the remaining locals would be subject to forced [[Germanization]]. All attempts by the Byelorussian representatives to request self-governance for the occupied Byelorussia led to German repressions against those who voiced such requests.<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1976-127-31A, Wilhelm Kube in Minsk.jpg|thumb|right|''Generalreichskommissar'' [[Wilhelm Kube]] in [[Minsk]], May 1943]]\n''Generalreichskommissar'' [[Wilhelm Kube]] was appointed the German administrator of the area. He had his command center established in [[Minsk]] with a second ''Kommissar'' in [[Baranovichi]]. In September 1943, Kube was killed by his Byelorussian mistress, who planted a bomb in his bed coerced by the Soviet agents who knew where her son was.<ref name=\"Wilson-PDF\"/>\n\nIn order to drum up fresh troops for the front inside ''[[Reichskommissariat Ostland]]'' and to stimulate support from the Belarusian population and elites,<ref name=hardzijenka/> General [[Reinhard Gehlen]] suggested to the German High Command that some concessions be made to the Belarusian collaborators in the form of a [[puppet state]].<ref name=\"Wilson-PDF\"/> The ''semi-autonomous'' local government was founded by Nazi Germany in December 1943, and named the Byelorussian  Central Council. [[Radas\u0142a\u016d Astro\u016dski]], the mayor of Smolensk at that time, was appointed its president.<ref name=\"Wilson\"/> General [[Curt von Gottberg|Kurt von Gottberg]] who replaced Kube, named the Belarusian politician [[Ivan Yermachenka]], arriving from Prague, the \"Advisor on Belarusian affairs\".<ref name=\"Wilson-PDF\">{{cite web |url=http://mizna.ru/docs/2/1212/conv_1/file1.pdf |title=The Traumatic Twentieth Century |publisher=Yale University Press |work=Belarus: the last European dictatorship |year=2011 |accessdate=10 July 2014 |author=Andrew Wilson |pages=109&ndash;110 |format=PDF file, direct download 16.4 MB |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714144611/http://mizna.ru/docs/2/1212/conv_1/file1.pdf |archivedate=14 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\n==Functions and work==\nThe Byelorussian Central Council only had a limited role in governing, with the key decisions being taken by the German administration of the ''Generalbezirk Wei\u00dfruthenien''. The Council mostly managed social affairs as well as culture and education.<ref name=hardzijenka>{{cite web | url = http://www.bielarus.org/open.php?n=492&a=3 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060928014900/http://www.bielarus.org/open.php?n=492&a=3 | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2006-09-28 | title = \u0414\u0410 \u040e\u0413\u041e\u0414\u041a\u0410\u040e \u0411\u0415\u041b\u0410\u0420\u0423\u0421\u041a\u0410\u0419 \u0426\u042d\u041d\u0422\u0420\u0410\u041b\u042c\u041d\u0410\u0419 \u0420\u0410\u0414\u042b - \u0420\u0430\u0437\u0432\u0430\u0433\u0456 \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0434\u043e\u0433\u0430 \u0433\u0456\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u044b\u043a\u0430 | trans-title = The anniversary of the Belarusian Central Council - ideas from a young historian | last = Hardzijenka | first = Aleh | date = January 2004 | website = Bielarus.org | publisher = Bielarus Newspaper | access-date = 10 January 2017 | language = Belarusian }}</ref> The Council had twelve departments including: Education, science and culture; Propaganda and press; Social security; Finance; Youth affairs; Religion; Control; Administrative issues; Economy; National minorities; and [[Belarusian Home Defence|Home Defense]].<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\nThe Byelorussian Central Council oversaw the activities of Byelorussian civic organizations established earlier under German permission including: Union of Byelorussian Youth; Byelorussian Scientific Society; Byelorussian Cultural Association; Byelorussian Self-Help; and labour unions.<ref name=hardzijenka/> The Council has managed to widen the usage of the Byelorussian language in schools and in public life, worked on the opening of a university.<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\nUnlike earlier Byelorussian collaborationist organizations, the Byelorussian Central Council was better positioned with the German authorities to protect the interests of the Byelorussian population from the Germans.<ref name=hardzijenka/>{{better source|date=February 2017}}\n\n==Policy on religion==\nThe ''SS'' authorised an [[Autocephaly|autocephalous]] [[Belarusian Orthodox Church]] independent from the [[Patriarch of Moscow]] who, similarly, was used by the Soviet atheists to rally Russians against the Germans. The priests had considerable influence with the peasantry and actively supported the defeat of Soviet Russia, which had terrorized Christians in [[West Belarus]] after the joint Soviet [[Soviet invasion of Poland|invasion of Poland]] of September 17, 1939.<ref name=\"1000dokumente\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.1000dokumente.de/index.html?c=dokument_de&dokument=0025_pak&object=facsimile&pimage=1&v=100&nav=&l=de |type= facsimile |title= 100(0) Schl\u00fcsseldokumente |place= [[Germany|DE]] |accessdate= 17 September 2009 |ref= harv}}.</ref>\n\n==Byelorussian Home Defence (BKA)==\n{{Main|Byelorussian Home Defence}}\n  [[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-1991-0206-506, Wei\u00dfrussland, Minsk.jpg|thumb|[[Byelorussian Home Defence]] (BKA) parading in [[Minsk]] <ref name=\"Wilson\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jZJntMQtkSYC&q=%28BKA%29 |title=Belarus: The Last European Dictatorship |publisher=Yale University Press |year=2011 |accessdate=10 July 2014 |author=Andrew Wilson |pages=109, 110, 113 |isbn=0300134355 | format=Google Books preview}}</ref>]]\nIn March 1944, the Byelorussian Central Council organized a universal military conscription among the young Belarusians. The Belarusian Home Defence Force (''Bielaruskaja Krajovaja Abarona'', BKA) was formed, with 28,000 soldiers ready for training, aided by a few thousand members of the [[Belarusian Auxiliary Police]] battalions.<ref name=\"Piotrowski155\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hC0-dk7vpM8C&q=%22forty+thousand+volunteers%22#v=snippet&q=%22forty%20thousand%20volunteers%22&f=false | title=Belorussian Collaboration | publisher=McFarland | work=Poland's Holocaust: Ethnic Strife, Collaboration with Occupying Forces and Genocide in the Second Republic, 1918-1947 | date=1998 | accessdate=6 February 2015 | author=Tadeusz Piotrowski | pages=155 | isbn=0786403713}}</ref>\n\nAfter the retreat of Germans from Byelorussia, the Byelorussian Home Defence was absorbed into ''[[30th Waffen Grenadier Division of the SS|30. Waffen-Grenadier-Division der SS-Russische No 2.]]''. This infantry division formed from the remnants of the [[29th Waffen-SS Division]], included both Belarusian and Ukrainian units. The Germans had set up an officers' school and issued uniforms with a [[Waffen-SS]] Storm-brigade Belarus designation. Orders were issued for Belarusian forces to be absorbed by [[Andrey Vlasov]]'s [[Russian Army of Liberation]]; but Astro\u016dski opposed this. He also sabotaged the idea of the \"[[Committee for the Liberation of the Peoples of Russia]]\", since he did not wanted to align himself with Russians.\n\nOther members of BKA and the Byelorussian Auxiliary Police were recruited by SS Colonel [[Otto Skorzeny]] for training in Dahlwitz near [[Berlin]], to make special undercover strikes behind the enemy lines. These units were part of a clandestine operation known as ''Liebes K\u00e4tzchen'' stretched from the Baltics to the Black Sea. The Byelorussian \"[[\u010corny Kot|Black Cat]]\" guerrilla group was led by [[Michas' Vitushka]]. They operated in [[Belavezha Forest]] (Bia\u0142owie\u017ca) against the Soviet forces in anti-communist operations throughout 1945 but with little success.<ref name=\"PartyzanFilm\">{{cite journal | url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/201323579/BielaruskiRezystans-1 | title=Belarusian Resistance, documentary by PartyzanFilm 2008 (transcript) | publisher=Scribd.com | work=Based on Bialoruski ruch oporu by Siarhiej Jorsz | date=January 22, 2014 | accessdate=19 February 2015 | author=Dawid Wowra}}</ref><ref name=\"wilson109\">Wilson 2011, [https://books.google.com/books?id=jZJntMQtkSYC&q=%22Black+Cat%22+#v=snippet&q=%22Black%20Cat%22&f=false  p. 109. Operation Black Cat.]</ref><ref name=\"MI6\">{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/mi6insidecovertw00dorr | url-access=registration | quote=Black Cat. | title=MI6: Inside the Covert World | publisher=Simon and Schuster | work=Belorussia | date=2002 | accessdate=19 February 2015 | author=Stephen Dorril | page=[https://archive.org/details/mi6insidecovertw00dorr/page/217 217] | ISBN=0743217780}}</ref><ref name=\"MJC167\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4zSGR3fBfUcC&q=%22Black+Cat%22#v=snippet&q=%22Black%20Cat%22&f=false | title=Intermarium: The Land between the Black and Baltic Seas | publisher=Transaction Publishers | work=The Second Soviet Occupation | date=2012 | accessdate=19 February 2015 | author=Marek Jan Chodakiewicz | page=167 }}</ref> Infiltrated by NKVD, they were destroyed in 1945.<ref name=\"Dudar\">{{cite web|url=http://geocities.com/dudar2000/Bcc.htm |title=Belarusian \"Black Cats\" of Otto Skorzeny |publisher=Internet Archive |work=John Loftus \"The Belarus Secret\", edited by Nathan Miller, Alfred A. Knopf Inc., New York, 1982. |ISBN=0-394-52292-3 |date=March 25, 1999 |accessdate=19 February 2015 |author=Dudar |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025235435/http://geocities.com/dudar2000/Bcc.htm |archivedate=October 25, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n==Exile==\nIn 1944, with the advance of the [[Red Army]] towards the West, the Byelorussian Central Council evacuated with the retreating Germans to [[East Prussia]]n and [[Poland|Polish]] lands still under the control of Nazi Germany.\n\nA few days before the evacuation, the BCR held a congress in Minsk, titled the Second All-Byelorussian Congress. The meeting gathered 1039 delegates from various regions of Belarus and from Byelorussian emigre organizations.<ref name=hardz_2ubk>http://www.bielarus.org/open.php?n=497&a=10</ref> The congress confirmed the declaration of independence of Belarus and declared the Belarusian Central Council as the supreme Belarusian representative body. The aim of the meeting was for the BCR to gain legitimacy basing on a decision by representatives of the Belarusian society rather than on a decision by the German administration.<ref name=hardz_2ubk/> The organizers feared provocations from both Soviet partisans and the Germans.<ref name=hardz_2ubk/>\n\nAfter evacuation, the leadership of the BCR has formed the base for Byelorussian self-organization in the post-war camps for [[Displaced person]]s.<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\nAt the end of 1945, Astro\u016dski held a special meeting of the \"Byelorussian Central Committee\" which decided to dissolve the government in order to avoid accusation of collaboration with the Nazis.<ref name=hardzijenka/>\n\nOn March 25, 1948, the Byelorussian Central Council renewed its activity in exile.<ref>[[Wojciech Roszkowski]], Jan Kofman (Hrsg.): ''Biographical Dictionary of Central and Eastern Europe in the Twentieth Century.'' Routledge, Abingdon u. a. 2015, {{ISBN|978-0-7656-1027-0}}, p. 39-40.</ref> It has been one of the main umbrella organizations of the Belarusian emigre community in the West till its de facto dissolution in 1995.\n\n==Presidents==\n* [[Radas\u0142a\u016d Astro\u016dski]] (1943 \u2014 1945 and 1948 \u2014 1976)\n* [[Nikandar Miadziejka]] (1977 \u2014 1987)\n* [[Michas Zuj]] (1988 \u2014 1995)\n* [[Vital Ciarpicki]] (1995)\n\n==See also==\n* [[German occupation of Byelorussia during World War II]]\n* [[Byelorussian collaboration with Nazi Germany]]\n* [[Byelorussia in World War II]]\n* [[Lokot Republic]] - native Russian state under indirect German control\n* [[Belarusian People's Republic]] - World War I-era Belarusian state\n* [[Byelorussian SSR]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* Arnold Toynbee, Veronica Toynbee, ''et al.'', ''La Europa de Hitler'' (Spanish tr. of ''Hitler's Europe''), Ed Vergara, Barcelona, Esp, 1958 reprinted in 1986 by Madrid Sarpe D.L., Section VI: \"Occupied lands and Satellite Countries in East Europe\", Chapter II: Ostland, P.253-259. {{OCLC|434840263}}\n* Ostland Footnotes: P.253-259.\n\n{{WWIIHistory}}\n\n[[Category:Belarus in World War II]]\n[[Category:Belarusian collaboration with Nazi Germany]]\n[[Category:Belarusian Central Council]]\n[[Category:Belarusian independence movement]]\n[[Category:Reichskommissariat Ostland]]\n[[Category:Military history of the Soviet Union during World War II]]\n[[Category:Germany\u2013Soviet Union relations]]\n[[Category:Collaboration with the Axis Powers]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Brigade Piron", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Byelorussian_Central_Council"}
{"title_page": "Catherine Conybeare", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Catherine Conybeare Annaba 2016.jpg|thumb|300px|right|Catherine Conybeare sitting on the [[Cathedral|episcopal seat]] of [[Augustine of Hippo]] at the Basilica Pacis in [[Annaba]] in 2016. The modern [[Saint Augustin Basilica|Basilica of Saint Augustine]] is in the distance]]\n'''Catherine Mary Conybeare'''  (born 1966) is an academic and [[Philology|philologist]] and an authority on [[Augustine of Hippo]]. She is currently Leslie Clark Professor in the Humanities at [[Bryn Mawr College]] in [[Pennsylvania]].<ref name=Bryn>[https://www.brynmawr.edu/people/catherine-conybeare Catherine Conybeare \u2013 Academic Profile] at [[Bryn Mawr College]]</ref><ref>[http://medieval.utoronto.ca/catherine-conybeare/ Profile on Catherine Conybeare] \u2013 [[University of Toronto]] website</ref><ref>[https://global.oup.com/academic/product/the-irrational-augustine-9780199262083?cc=us&lang=en& ''The Irrational Augustine''] \u2013 [[Oxford University Press]] {{ISBN|9780199262083}}</ref>\n\n==Academic career==\nConybeare was born in 1966 at [[Bristol]] in the United Kingdom<ref>[https://search.ancestry.co.uk/cgi-bin/sse.dll?indiv=1&dbid=8782&h=88580432&tid=&pid=&usePUB=true&_phsrc=djv1360&_phstart=successSource Catherine Mary Conybeare in the England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1916\u20132007] \u2013 [[Ancestry.com]] {{subscription}}</ref> and was educated at [[Oxford High School, England|Oxford High School]] (1975\u20131979), [[Simon Langton Girls' Grammar School]] (1979\u20131982), and [[The King's School, Canterbury]] (1982\u20131984). She read Classics at [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], 1985\u20131989) and did graduate work in Medieval Studies at the [[University of Toronto]] (MA, 1991; PhD, 1997) under the supervision of [[Brian Stock (historian)|Brian Stock]].<ref>\"Conybeare, Catherine\"  Contemporary Authors. Encyclopedia.com. 30 March 2019 <https://www.encyclopedia.com></ref>  From 1996 to 2002 she was at the [[University of Manchester]], including three years as a British Academy Post-Doctoral Fellow in the Department of Classics and Ancient History. She has been Director of the Graduate Group in Archaeology, Classics, and History of Art at [[Bryn Mawr College]] (2006\u20132014), where she was promoted to Full Professor in the Department of Greek, Latin, and Classical Studies in 2011; Associate Professor (2005\u20132011), and Assistant Professor (2002\u20132005).<ref name=Vitae>[http://fliphtml5.com/iiob/dkmu/basic Catherine Conybeare \u2013 Curriculum Vitae: April 2015]</ref>\n\nHer research centres on late Antiquity, and especially on the writings of [[Augustine of Hippo]].<ref name=Bryn/> She was a W. John Bennett Distinguished Visiting\u00a0Scholar at the [[Pontifical Institute of Mediaeval Studies|Pontifical Institute]] and the\u00a0[[Centre for Medieval Studies, Toronto|Centre for Medieval Studies]] in Toronto (2014\u20132015).<ref>[http://www.pims.ca/academics/visiting-scholars/curriculum/catherine-conybeare Profile for Catherine Conybeare \u2013 Pontifical Institute and Centre For Medieval Studies website]</ref> In 2015 she was a Visiting Fellow at the [[Centre for Research in the Arts, Social Sciences and Humanities]] (CRASSH) at the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>[http://www.crassh.cam.ac.uk/people/profile/catherine-conybeare Catherine Conybeare \u2013 Centre for Research in the Arts, Social Sciences and Humanities website]</ref>\n\nIn 2019\u20132020 she is Visiting Fellow at [[All Souls College, Oxford]], and then at [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]. She is also the recipient of a fellowship from the [[American Council of Learned Societies]] and a [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] from the [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial\u00a0Foundation]].\n<ref>[https://www.acls.org/news/04-02-2019 Announcing the 2019 ACLS Fellows] \u2013 [[American Council of Learned Societies]]</ref>\n\nConybeare has two sons: Gabriel (born 1994) and Hilary (born 2000). She is also a keen amateur musician and learns the organ with Parker Kitterman at [[Christ Church, Philadelphia]].\n\n==Publications==\nConybeare has published widely on such topics as aurality, touch, violence, and the self and is the author of ''The Routledge Guidebook to Augustine's Confessions'' (2016);<ref>[https://www.routledge.com/The-Routledge-Guidebook-to-Augustines-Confessions/Conybeare/p/book/9781138847972 ''The Routledge Guidebook to Augustine's Confessions''] \u2013 [[Routledge]]</ref> ''The Laughter of Sarah: Biblical Exegesis, Feminist Theory, and the Concept of Delight'' (2013), which examines the place of delight in Judaeo-Christian interpretative tradition;<ref>[http://www.palgrave.com/us/book/9781137373113 ''The Laughter of Sarah: Biblical Exegesis, Feminist Theory, and the Concept of Delight''], Palgrave MacMillan {{ISBN|978-1-137-37091-4}}</ref><ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=wkuVBgAAQBAJ&pg=PR13&lpg=PR13&dq=catherine+conybeare+bristol&source=bl&ots=2CzbEH4xpr&sig=ACfU3U02IHIoAt9FpZn7kPNpmcbKNxXNMQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjN95X34KnhAhXxRhUIHVi-BdQQ6AEwDnoECAYQAQ#v=onepage&q=catherine%20conybeare%20bristol&f=false Catherine Conybeare  (contributor), ''A Companion to Augustine''], Wiley Blackwell (2015) \u2013 [[Google Books]] pg. xiii {{ISBN|978-1-119-02555-9}}</ref> ''The Irrational Augustine'' (2006) which charts Augustine's progress from neo-Platonism to incarnational theology in his Cassiciacum dialogues;<ref>[http://www.oxfordscholarship.com/view/10.1093/019926208x.001.0001/acprof-9780199262083  ''The Irrational Augustine''] , [[Oxford University Press]] \u2013 {{ISBN|9780199262083}}</ref> and ''Paulinus Noster: Self and Symbols in the Letters of [[Paulinus of Nola]]'' (2000), looking at the formation of spiritual community through early Christian letter collections.<ref>[http://bmcr.brynmawr.edu/2002/2002-05-05.html ''Paulinus Noster: Self and Symbols in the Letters of Paulinus of Nola''] \u2013 [[Oxford University Press]] \u2013 {{ISBN|0-19-924072-8}}</ref>\n\nShe is currently working on her next monograph, ''Augustine the African'', and is co-editing with [[Simon Goldhill]] ''Philology's Shadow'', a collection of essays exploring the interdependence of Theology and classical [[philology]].<ref name=Bryn/>\n\nConybeare is also editor of the new series from [[Cambridge University Press]], 'Cultures of Latin from Antiquity to the Enlightenment'.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=q6kUDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Catherine+Conybeare%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjoqNO3gKrhAhXnRxUIHcEqD-kQ6AEIOTAC#v=onepage&q&f=false Text of ''The Irrational Augustine''] (2006) \u2013 [[Google Books]]\n*[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=D00TDAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Catherine+Conybeare%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjoqNO3gKrhAhXnRxUIHcEqD-kQ6AEIQDAD#v=onepage&q&f=false Text of ''Paulinus Noster: Self and Symbols in the Letters of Paulinus of Nola''] (2000) \u2013 [[Google Books]]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conybeare, Catherine}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Bristol]]\n[[Category:People educated at Oxford High School, England]]\n[[Category:People educated at The King's School, Canterbury]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Corpus Christi College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Classical scholars of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Manchester]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Bryn Mawr College faculty]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Women philologists]]\n[[Category:English philologists]]\n[[Category:British classical philologists]]\n[[Category:Classical philologists]]\n[[Category:Scholars of Latin literature]]\n[[Category:ACLS Fellows]]\n[[Category:Guggenheim Fellows]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Engva